00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:15.230
Well the momentum
diffusion coefficient

00:38:15.230 --> 00:38:18.180
tells you that P
square is simply

00:38:18.180 --> 00:38:19.830
growing as a function of time.

00:38:19.830 --> 00:38:22.170
If you have a cold cloud
and you heat it up,

00:38:22.170 --> 00:38:25.420
you can describe the heating
by the temporal growth

00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:27.440
of P square.

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:29.480
If you don't like
momentum, divide P

00:38:29.480 --> 00:38:31.940
squared by 2m you have
the kinetic energy, which

00:38:31.940 --> 00:38:33.140
increases.

00:38:33.140 --> 00:38:36.390
So it is this momentum
diffusion coefficient.

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:40.075
And if you have a cloud which
moves with an average momentum,

00:38:40.075 --> 00:38:43.410
you only want to have the P
square minus P average square.

00:38:43.410 --> 00:38:46.560
But if you think about a
cloud which is being cooled,

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:49.750
the second term is 0.

00:38:49.750 --> 00:38:51.690
So the momentum
diffusion coefficient

00:38:51.690 --> 00:38:54.280
is the derivative of P square.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:58.030
But the derivative of
P is simply the force.

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:02.160
So therefore we can absorb the
derivative by replacing P--

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:04.920
at least one of the
P's-- by the force.

00:39:04.920 --> 00:39:07.900
And we can now get
rid of to second P

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:09.610
of the second
occurrence of momentum

00:39:09.610 --> 00:39:12.510
by saying well momentum
is derivative of force.

00:39:16.120 --> 00:39:18.580
