00:46:22.910 --> 00:46:28.710
and you integrate over it you
have an exponential decay.

00:46:28.710 --> 00:46:33.740
But instead of integrating
over the exponential decay

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:36.000
you can just take
the force squared

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:39.665
and multiply it with the
average time the atom stays.

00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:47.700
In other words, if I have an
exponentially decaying function

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.900
I can always approximate it
by the function of T equals

00:46:50.900 --> 00:46:53.340
0 times the time.

00:46:53.340 --> 00:46:54.920
And what you are
asking me now is

00:46:54.920 --> 00:46:58.100
is the time the one over E
time, or is it an average time?

00:46:58.100 --> 00:46:59.962
What is the correct
time to use here?

00:46:59.962 --> 00:47:01.837
AUDIENCE: I guess when
the time scale depends

00:47:01.837 --> 00:47:06.228
on how the correlations decay
for [INAUDIBLE] different.

00:47:09.610 --> 00:47:13.610
PROFESSOR: Yes, OK, I agree.

00:47:13.610 --> 00:47:16.540
The shape of the decay of
the correlation function

00:47:16.540 --> 00:47:17.460
would matter.

00:47:17.460 --> 00:47:19.240
I'm not going into that.

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:21.590
But what I'm sort
of assuming here

00:47:21.590 --> 00:47:25.470
is that the correlation
function indicated with time

00:47:25.470 --> 00:47:29.130
is the correlation function of
T equals 0 times the correlation

00:47:29.130 --> 00:47:30.290
time.

00:47:30.290 --> 00:47:32.940
And how the correlation
time is related

00:47:32.940 --> 00:47:34.890
to the exponential
time, or if there's

00:47:34.890 --> 00:47:39.090
a small prefactor and such,
that may depend on details.

00:47:39.090 --> 00:47:40.305
Yes, you're right.

00:47:40.305 --> 00:47:41.646
I've swept this under the rug.

00:47:53.502 --> 00:47:54.210
How are we doing?

00:47:54.210 --> 00:47:54.710
Good.

00:47:57.970 --> 00:47:59.640
Let me just summarize.

00:47:59.640 --> 00:48:02.630
The dressed atom
picture has given us

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:06.200
two pieces of major insight
into the stimulated force.

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:12.040
The first one is that the
atom experience is always

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:15.880
opposite forces in the
two dressed levels.

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:17.940
And it is the
population imbalance

00:48:17.940 --> 00:48:22.100
between the two dressed levels
which results in a net force.

00:48:22.100 --> 00:48:24.210
And this requires
either red detuning,

00:48:24.210 --> 00:48:25.890
then the force is
repulsive, or blue

00:48:25.890 --> 00:48:27.710
detuning-- sorry,
red detuning then

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:29.834
the force is attractive,
or blue detuning then it's

00:48:29.834 --> 00:48:31.570
a force repulsive.

00:48:31.570 --> 00:48:34.650
Second, with this
time lag thing,

00:48:34.650 --> 00:48:38.210
we understand that time
lag, non-adiabaticity,

00:48:38.210 --> 00:48:40.380
is the way to get cooling.

00:48:40.380 --> 00:48:43.335
And the third thing we have
learned, when the atom does

00:48:43.335 --> 00:48:47.790
a radiative cascade the force--
when it goes from the upper

00:48:47.790 --> 00:48:49.930
to the lower dressed
level-- the force

00:48:49.930 --> 00:48:52.260
is suddenly reversing it's sign.

00:48:52.260 --> 00:48:56.070
And this causes fluctuations,
this shakes up atom,

00:48:56.070 --> 00:48:57.990
and this causes heating.

00:48:57.990 --> 00:49:02.730
And this has nothing to do with
the other heating mechanism we

00:49:02.730 --> 00:49:05.300
discussed earlier,
namely every time there

00:49:05.300 --> 00:49:07.590
is spontaneous emission
there's a random recoil.

00:49:11.080 --> 00:49:14.740
In strong laser fields
the fluctuations

00:49:14.740 --> 00:49:16.209
of the stimulated
force, which has

00:49:16.209 --> 00:49:17.875
nothing to do with
spontaneous emission,

00:49:17.875 --> 00:49:20.590
are much, much larger
than the photon recoil.

00:49:20.590 --> 00:49:22.630
So therefore for
strong laser fields,

00:49:22.630 --> 00:49:26.450
it is this alternation
of the force when

00:49:26.450 --> 00:49:28.730
atoms switch dressed
energy levels, which

00:49:28.730 --> 00:49:30.460
is responsible for
most of the heating.

00:49:46.460 --> 00:49:49.270
I want to come now to another
physical situation, which

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:50.580
is actually wonderful.

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:52.860
You learn about
Sisyphus cooling.

00:49:52.860 --> 00:49:55.090
Everybody in cold atoms
speaks about Sisyphus

00:49:55.090 --> 00:50:00.070
cooling because it's a very,
very elegant cooling scheme.

00:50:00.070 --> 00:50:04.040
We usually apply in the
laboratory Sisyphus cooling

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:06.090
when we do polarization
gradient cooling.

00:50:06.090 --> 00:50:08.050
I will say you a
few things later.

00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:11.250
But this is much, much harder
to understand than the Sisyphus

00:50:11.250 --> 00:50:16.250
cooling, which takes place
for a two level atom moving

00:50:16.250 --> 00:50:19.790
through a blue
detuned standing wave.

00:50:19.790 --> 00:50:21.850
So in other words,
I try to explain now

00:50:21.850 --> 00:50:24.420
to you what Sisyphus cooling is.

00:50:24.420 --> 00:50:29.260
The relevant application
is multi-level polarization

00:50:29.260 --> 00:50:31.600
gradient cooling, which
I give you an idea,

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:33.480
but it's hard to fully describe.

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:37.790
But here, in our current
discussion on the two level

00:50:37.790 --> 00:50:42.590
atom interacting with one laser
beam, or one standing wave,

00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:45.255
we find the simplest
physical realization

00:50:45.255 --> 00:50:47.320
of Sisyphus cooling.

00:50:47.320 --> 00:50:50.020
So just to make sure that you
are following the argument,

00:50:50.020 --> 00:50:54.200
I have so far explained to you
why blue detuned light cools

00:50:54.200 --> 00:50:57.580
in the limit of very
small velocities.

00:50:57.580 --> 00:51:01.200
Very small velocity means
we did a first order Taylor

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:04.600
expansion in this lag time.

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:08.820
But now I want to discuss with
you a different regime, namely

00:51:08.820 --> 00:51:11.730
that the atom moves
with a velocity such

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:18.040
that it can go up and down
several periods of the standing

00:51:18.040 --> 00:51:22.060
wave before it does
spontaneous emission.

00:51:22.060 --> 00:51:25.130
So before when we discussed
the friction coefficient,

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:26.950
the velocity was infinitesimal.

00:51:26.950 --> 00:51:29.620
But now I assume that
the velocity is such

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:31.980
that the atom can
surf a few waves

00:51:31.980 --> 00:51:34.590
and then it will
spontaneously emit.

00:51:34.590 --> 00:51:37.820
And let me assume that
we are blue detuned.

00:51:37.820 --> 00:51:43.970
So the atom, let's say here,
where the splitting is minimum,

00:51:43.970 --> 00:51:45.940
well this is where
we don't have light.

00:51:45.940 --> 00:51:48.960
The generalized Rabi frequency
is just the detuning.

00:51:48.960 --> 00:51:51.560
So we are in a node
of the standing wave.

00:51:51.560 --> 00:51:54.220
And then the atom starts
in the ground state,

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:57.660
and it experiences
the periodic potential

00:51:57.660 --> 00:52:00.700
due to the standing wave.

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:05.720
But we want to now ask, OK,
when will spontaneous emission

00:52:05.720 --> 00:52:07.800
happen in this picture?

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:11.040
Well, it cannot happen here,
when the atom is in the ground

00:52:11.040 --> 00:52:12.670
state, when there is not light.

00:52:12.670 --> 00:52:16.910
But where there is light, when
the atoms move to an anti-node,

00:52:16.910 --> 00:52:21.560
there is a mixture, indicated
in red, of the excited state.

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:24.950
So in other words, when an
atom does this roller coaster,

00:52:24.950 --> 00:52:29.800
it will most likely emit a
photon-- either the carrier

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:32.190
or one of the
sidebands-- when it

00:52:32.190 --> 00:52:37.290
is at the maximum of the
potential corresponding

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:42.740
to an anti-node where it
experiences the light.

00:52:42.740 --> 00:52:46.180
OK, when the atom
emits on the carrier

00:52:46.180 --> 00:52:48.790
it goes from the
upper dressed level

00:52:48.790 --> 00:52:50.480
to the upper dressed level.

00:52:50.480 --> 00:52:51.920
Then sort of
nothing has happened

00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:54.290
because the atom is in
the same dressed level.

00:52:54.290 --> 00:52:57.650
Let me now discuss the case
when something happens.

00:52:57.650 --> 00:53:02.130
And this is when the atom decays
from the upper dressed level

00:53:02.130 --> 00:53:04.830
to the lower dressed level.

00:53:04.830 --> 00:53:08.580
And at least for weak excitation
the lower dressed level

00:53:08.580 --> 00:53:11.410
corresponds to
the excited state.

00:53:11.410 --> 00:53:14.770
In other words, when
there is no light,

00:53:14.770 --> 00:53:17.190
the upper dressed
level was ground state,

00:53:17.190 --> 00:53:21.160
the lower dressed
level is excited state.

00:53:21.160 --> 00:53:23.870
But what happens now is
actually interesting,

00:53:23.870 --> 00:53:26.710
the atom had to
climb up the hill.

00:53:26.710 --> 00:53:29.720
But the spontaneous emission
to the lower dressed level

00:53:29.720 --> 00:53:32.110
takes the atom to the bottom.

00:53:32.110 --> 00:53:35.600
So you can see, on average,
it has climbed a hill here,

00:53:35.600 --> 00:53:37.690
but now it is at the bottom.

00:53:37.690 --> 00:53:40.810
And now we're going to ask
how does the atom get out

00:53:40.810 --> 00:53:42.850
of the lower dressed level?

00:53:42.850 --> 00:53:45.490
Well, the lower
dressed level is mainly

00:53:45.490 --> 00:53:50.830
excited-- is 100% excited
if there is no light.

00:53:50.830 --> 00:53:54.460
But if there is light, and
light means the generalized Rabi

00:53:54.460 --> 00:53:57.920
frequency is larger, the
excited state has now in it

00:53:57.920 --> 00:54:00.340
mixture of the ground
state because the light

00:54:00.340 --> 00:54:03.580
mixes ground and excited state.

00:54:03.580 --> 00:54:06.475
So now, of course,
whenever there is red

00:54:06.475 --> 00:54:08.460
you can spontaneously emit.

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:11.960
But there is a
probability that the atom

00:54:11.960 --> 00:54:15.770
is more likely to emit when you
are in a purely excited state,

00:54:15.770 --> 00:54:17.910
and not in a mixed state.

00:54:17.910 --> 00:54:20.930
So now, talking about
the lower manifold,

00:54:20.930 --> 00:54:22.860
the atom does it's
roller coaster.

00:54:22.860 --> 00:54:24.960
It has a velocity
that it can cover

00:54:24.960 --> 00:54:29.280
several periods of the
standing wave in one lifetime.

00:54:29.280 --> 00:54:32.150
But there is a higher
probability for the atom

00:54:32.150 --> 00:54:36.060
now to emit when it
is on top of the hill.

00:54:36.060 --> 00:54:37.610
So that's remarkable.

00:54:37.610 --> 00:54:39.710
We have the upper dressed level.

00:54:39.710 --> 00:54:41.450
We have the lower dressed level.

00:54:41.450 --> 00:54:44.100
The atom is doing
the roller coaster.

00:54:44.100 --> 00:54:48.950
But whenever it emits a
sideband, whenever it switches

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:52.300
state, it mainly
does it by emitting

00:54:52.300 --> 00:54:54.450
at the top of the hill.

00:54:54.450 --> 00:54:56.300
And after the
spontaneous emission

00:54:56.300 --> 00:54:59.000
it finds itself at the
bottom of the hill.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:02.950
So on average the atom
is climbing more up hills

00:55:02.950 --> 00:55:05.510
than down hills.

00:55:05.510 --> 00:55:07.240
And this is called
Sisyphus cooling.

00:55:07.240 --> 00:55:10.070
I think you've all heard
about the Greek myth of King

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:13.670
Sisyphus, who was condemned.

00:55:13.670 --> 00:55:15.770
He challenged the gods
and he got his punishment.

00:55:15.770 --> 00:55:17.920
And his punishment
was that he always

00:55:17.920 --> 00:55:20.210
has to roll a stone up the hill.

00:55:20.210 --> 00:55:22.600
And when he's done
the stone falls down

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:24.740
and he has to roll the stone up.

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:27.710
So in other words, we
have condemned the atoms

00:55:27.710 --> 00:55:28.880
to the same verdict.

00:55:28.880 --> 00:55:31.480
They always have to
go up hill to work.

00:55:31.480 --> 00:55:33.810
Then they fall down
hill with the help

00:55:33.810 --> 00:55:35.480
of a spontaneous photon.

00:55:35.480 --> 00:55:38.210
But then they have
to climb up hill.

00:55:38.210 --> 00:55:43.090
And it is the uphill climb where
the experience and net friction

00:55:43.090 --> 00:55:47.720
force, which cools the
atoms down and reduces

00:55:47.720 --> 00:55:48.650
their kinetic energy.

00:55:56.090 --> 00:55:58.980
So this is Sisyphus cooling.

00:55:58.980 --> 00:56:03.640
And since I need it
in a few minutes,

00:56:03.640 --> 00:56:07.950
I just wrote down for you, based
on this simple and wonderfully

00:56:07.950 --> 00:56:10.515
elegant picture,
how much energy does

00:56:10.515 --> 00:56:12.230
the atom lose per unit time?

00:56:12.230 --> 00:56:14.160
What is the cooling rate?

00:56:14.160 --> 00:56:17.200
Well it's clear that
the cooling rate

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:20.120
comes when the atom switches
from one dressed energy

00:56:20.120 --> 00:56:23.650
level to the next, because
nothing happens on the carrier.

00:56:23.650 --> 00:56:26.900
So it is the transition state
between dressed level one

00:56:26.900 --> 00:56:28.920
and dressed level two.

00:56:28.920 --> 00:56:31.620
And then we multiply
with mu naught

00:56:31.620 --> 00:56:34.710
the depths of the optical
lattice, because it

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:39.440
is this energy difference which
is extracted from the atom.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:46.440
You may ask, OK what
is time limiting?

00:56:46.440 --> 00:56:50.550
It's really the transition rate
form the first dressed level,

00:56:50.550 --> 00:56:55.510
which is mainly ground state, to
the other dressed level, which

00:56:55.510 --> 00:56:57.550
is mainly exciting state.

00:56:57.550 --> 00:57:00.570
Because once the atom is in
this level, which is mainly

00:57:00.570 --> 00:57:03.800
the excited state,
it will pretty much

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:06.900
do the next transition
at a rate which

00:57:06.900 --> 00:57:09.500
corresponds to the
spontaneous emission rate.

00:57:09.500 --> 00:57:14.810
So in other words, if you're
not fully on resonance,

00:57:14.810 --> 00:57:17.070
or if you're not
situated in laser power,

00:57:17.070 --> 00:57:20.860
the rate, one, two, is slower
than the rate two, one.

00:57:20.860 --> 00:57:23.311
And therefore this rate
is the rate limiting step.

00:57:26.610 --> 00:57:32.690
Let me show you
just a few pictures.

00:57:32.690 --> 00:57:37.230
What I'm just explaining to
you was explored very early on,

00:57:37.230 --> 00:57:40.450
just have to sort of put you
back that it was in the mid

00:57:40.450 --> 00:57:44.640
'80s, '82, '83, '84, that people
developed [INAUDIBLE] slowing.

00:57:44.640 --> 00:57:48.880
It was in '85 that optical
molasses with red detuned light

00:57:48.880 --> 00:57:51.230
was demonstrated
for the first time.

00:57:51.230 --> 00:57:54.500
It was in '86 that
the dipole trap

00:57:54.500 --> 00:57:56.290
was demonstrated by Steve Chu.

00:57:56.290 --> 00:57:58.840
And in '87 that Steve
Chu and Dave Pritchard

00:57:58.840 --> 00:58:00.790
introduced the
magneto optic trap.

00:58:00.790 --> 00:58:04.580
So the mid to late '80s
were fantastic times,

00:58:04.580 --> 00:58:09.070
where one important technique
was realized and demonstrated.

00:58:09.070 --> 00:58:13.000
And this was actually the
first major experimental paper

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:15.920
of a new laser
cooling group, which

00:58:15.920 --> 00:58:18.460
was founded by Claude
Cohen-Tonnoudji at the Ecole

00:58:18.460 --> 00:58:20.170
Normale Superieure in Paris.

00:58:20.170 --> 00:58:25.440
And it was exactly about cooling
atoms with stimulated emission,

00:58:25.440 --> 00:58:27.570
and this is blue molasses.

00:58:27.570 --> 00:58:31.210
And, I mean, you exactly
see here out of this paper,

00:58:31.210 --> 00:58:32.685
the Sisyphus cooling mechanism.

00:58:35.430 --> 00:58:40.860
And addressing the question
about red detuned light here,

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:42.950
this was actually
beam experiment.

00:58:42.950 --> 00:58:45.430
You head a blue
detuned standing wave,

00:58:45.430 --> 00:58:48.260
and you were sending
an atomic beam through.

00:58:48.260 --> 00:58:51.350
And if this atomic
beam was cooled,

00:58:51.350 --> 00:58:54.550
the divergence of the
atomic beam was reduced.

00:58:54.550 --> 00:58:59.030
So this experiment had only
one blue detuned standing wave

00:58:59.030 --> 00:59:02.630
and nothing else, because it
was not a trapping experiment.

00:59:02.630 --> 00:59:05.770
It was a beam
collimation experiment.

00:59:05.770 --> 00:59:08.670
And what is shown
here is that you

00:59:08.670 --> 00:59:12.230
have the original
atomic beam profile.

00:59:12.230 --> 00:59:17.920
And for blue detuned light
you make it narrower,

00:59:17.920 --> 00:59:19.390
so this is cooling.

00:59:19.390 --> 00:59:22.210
Whereas for red detuned
light you have a defocusing,

00:59:22.210 --> 00:59:23.500
which corresponds to heating.

00:59:28.770 --> 00:59:29.375
Any question?

00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:50.150
I want to wrap up the discussion
of the stimulated light force

00:59:50.150 --> 00:59:58.300
by discussing pretty
much everything again,

00:59:58.300 --> 01:00:01.430
but in the simplest
possibly limit.

01:00:01.430 --> 01:00:03.160
That's actually
something I haven't

01:00:03.160 --> 01:00:04.770
found in any text books.

01:00:04.770 --> 01:00:08.450
But when I derived
it for myself it

01:00:08.450 --> 01:00:10.450
helped me to really
understand it.

01:00:10.450 --> 01:00:13.960
It's sort of the perturbative
result of the dressed atom

01:00:13.960 --> 01:00:14.890
picture.

01:00:14.890 --> 01:00:16.640
So everything is simple.

01:00:16.640 --> 01:00:18.556
And by telling
you, look at this.

01:00:18.556 --> 01:00:20.601
You know this is
just EC stock shift.

01:00:20.601 --> 01:00:22.100
But in the dressed
atom picture it's

01:00:22.100 --> 01:00:24.480
a generalized Rabi
frequency, you suddenly

01:00:24.480 --> 01:00:27.600
understand the trivial
perturbative result

01:00:27.600 --> 01:00:30.770
and how it translates into
the dressed atom picture.

01:00:30.770 --> 01:00:34.230
So what I'm presenting you
now in the next 10 minutes,

01:00:34.230 --> 01:00:38.180
it provides a lot of
insight because it

01:00:38.180 --> 01:00:41.490
connects simple pictures.

01:00:41.490 --> 01:00:44.280
So I'm discussing
things here in the limit

01:00:44.280 --> 01:00:45.670
that the detuning is large.

01:00:45.670 --> 01:00:48.870
The detuning is larger
than the Rabi frequency,

01:00:48.870 --> 01:00:51.020
and spontaneous emission
rate is the smallest

01:00:51.020 --> 01:00:52.300
of the three rates.

01:00:52.300 --> 01:00:56.670
In that case, I can simply
do perturbation theory,

01:00:56.670 --> 01:00:58.680
and I want to show you.

01:00:58.680 --> 01:01:00.940
Also, because this
is pedagogical,

01:01:00.940 --> 01:01:03.950
I just want to show you how
the effects come together.

01:01:03.950 --> 01:01:07.230
I neglect all factors
on the order of unity.

01:01:07.230 --> 01:01:10.920
And I set h bar to 1.

01:01:10.920 --> 01:01:13.580
So let's assume we
have a standing wave.

01:01:13.580 --> 01:01:15.950
A standing wave is cosine KX.

01:01:21.090 --> 01:01:23.000
So we have an electric field.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:25.660
But we describe the electric
field with a Rabi frequency.

01:01:25.660 --> 01:01:29.200
So the Rabi frequency
forms a standing wave.

01:01:29.200 --> 01:01:31.430
Now what are the
two dressed states?

01:01:31.430 --> 01:01:35.900
The dressed states 1 and
2 are the bare states,

01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.670
ground and excited state.

01:01:37.670 --> 01:01:40.090
And then there a
perturbative mixture.

01:01:40.090 --> 01:01:43.440
And in first order
perturbation theory

01:01:43.440 --> 01:01:46.720
we take the matrix
element over the detuning.

01:01:46.720 --> 01:01:48.520
So one dressed
state is the ground

01:01:48.520 --> 01:01:50.980
state with a little bit
of excited stated mixed.

01:01:50.980 --> 01:01:54.300
The other dressed state is
the excited state, minus sign,

01:01:54.300 --> 01:01:56.270
little bit of ground stated mix.

01:01:56.270 --> 01:02:00.717
These are our two dressed
states in the trivial limit

01:02:00.717 --> 01:02:02.300
that we can apply
perturbation theory.

01:02:08.120 --> 01:02:10.840
What are now the
transition rates

01:02:10.840 --> 01:02:13.850
between the two dressed states?

01:02:13.850 --> 01:02:16.490
Well, we want to make
spontaneous emission

01:02:16.490 --> 01:02:19.480
from dressed state 1
to dressed state 2.

01:02:19.480 --> 01:02:23.880
We have to go from this small
mixture, which is the excited

01:02:23.880 --> 01:02:27.480
stated mixture, to
the ground state here.

01:02:27.480 --> 01:02:30.600
So therefore we get the
product of the two amplitudes,

01:02:30.600 --> 01:02:32.990
and then we multiply with gamma.

01:02:32.990 --> 01:02:36.220
Of course, most of-- yeah.

01:02:36.220 --> 01:02:39.020
So this is the rate to
go from dressed state

01:02:39.020 --> 01:02:41.210
1 to dressed state 2.

01:02:41.210 --> 01:02:43.720
What is the inverse rate to
go back from dressed state

01:02:43.720 --> 01:02:45.640
2 to dressed state 1?

01:02:45.640 --> 01:02:49.200
Well, you go from the excited
state to the ground state,

01:02:49.200 --> 01:02:53.130
multiply with gamma,
and that's what you get.

01:02:53.130 --> 01:02:58.400
Sure we have, in perturbation
theory, the coefficient is 1.

01:02:58.400 --> 01:03:00.620
It's only in higher
order perturbation theory

01:03:00.620 --> 01:03:05.490
that the coefficient of the
bare state becomes less than 1.

01:03:05.490 --> 01:03:06.650
So isn't that simple?

01:03:06.650 --> 01:03:09.200
We just discussed it with
all the cosine to the 4,

01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:10.050
sine to the 4.

01:03:10.050 --> 01:03:12.040
But now in perturbation
theory this

01:03:12.040 --> 01:03:16.380
is the rate for going
from dressed state 1 to 2.

01:03:16.380 --> 01:03:19.910
And this is the rate to
go the other way around.

01:03:19.910 --> 01:03:24.650
So what is our dressed
state potential?

01:03:24.650 --> 01:03:26.900
Well, the dressed
state potential

01:03:26.900 --> 01:03:30.300
is simply the EC
stock shift, which

01:03:30.300 --> 01:03:33.770
is opposite for the ground
and for the excited state.

01:03:33.770 --> 01:03:36.920
And the EC stock shift
in perturbation theory

01:03:36.920 --> 01:03:40.830
is nothing else than matrix
elements squared over detuning.

01:03:40.830 --> 01:03:42.840
So this is mu naught.

01:03:42.840 --> 01:03:46.740
This is the potential of the
standing wave experienced

01:03:46.740 --> 01:03:47.240
by the atom.

01:03:52.730 --> 01:03:54.780
Now we want to do
Sisyphus cooling.

01:03:54.780 --> 01:03:58.330
What is the cooling rate
in Sisyphus cooling?

01:03:58.330 --> 01:04:00.790
Well, remember,
Sisyphus cooling we

01:04:00.790 --> 01:04:02.840
assume that the
atom is fast enough

01:04:02.840 --> 01:04:07.250
to go over several
hills and valleys.

01:04:07.250 --> 01:04:13.610
The cooling rate is determined
by the rate at which the atoms

01:04:13.610 --> 01:04:16.650
switch dressed levels
times mu naught.

01:04:16.650 --> 01:04:20.400
And I can scroll back, but mu
naught was the EC stock effect,

01:04:20.400 --> 01:04:24.350
and gamma one, two was this
expression we had before.

01:04:24.350 --> 01:04:26.136
So therefore, in
the simple picture,

01:04:26.136 --> 01:04:27.510
while everything
is perturbative,

01:04:27.510 --> 01:04:32.220
we have a nice expression
for the cooling rate.

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:36.770
Well, now let's get something
non-trivial out of it.

01:04:36.770 --> 01:04:40.070
What is the friction
coefficient?

01:04:40.070 --> 01:04:42.690
Well, in many
situations I've plotted

01:04:42.690 --> 01:04:46.710
for you, the force
versus velocity.

01:04:46.710 --> 01:04:51.200
Now I want to plot for you the
cooling rate versus velocity.

01:04:51.200 --> 01:04:54.030
That means its force
times velocity.

01:04:54.030 --> 01:04:57.670
And as we just discussed, when
the velocity is sufficiently

01:04:57.670 --> 01:05:01.390
fast that the atom can go
over several hills and valleys

01:05:01.390 --> 01:05:04.030
in a spontaneous
lifetime, the cooling rate

01:05:04.030 --> 01:05:07.590
will saturate
because it is limited

01:05:07.590 --> 01:05:10.500
by the rate at which
the atom switches

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:11.530
between dressed levels.

01:05:15.810 --> 01:05:17.630
But now the question
is, if we want

01:05:17.630 --> 01:05:20.180
to understand what
happens at low velocities,

01:05:20.180 --> 01:05:23.560
how should we connect the two?

01:05:23.560 --> 01:05:27.010
Well, you can say we know,
for analytical reasons,

01:05:27.010 --> 01:05:30.850
that the force versus
velocity has to be linear.

01:05:30.850 --> 01:05:34.030
So the cooling rate, which
is another power of velocity,

01:05:34.030 --> 01:05:35.610
should be quadratic.

01:05:35.610 --> 01:05:39.160
And since I neglect all
factors on the order of unity,

01:05:39.160 --> 01:05:43.330
this is now the force is
friction coefficient times V.

01:05:43.330 --> 01:05:46.060
So therefore, what
I do in red here

01:05:46.060 --> 01:05:48.080
is a parabolic
approximation, which

01:05:48.080 --> 01:05:51.880
is alpha the cooling
rate times V squared.

01:05:51.880 --> 01:05:57.350
And now, if I want to
know what is alpha,

01:05:57.350 --> 01:06:00.310
I just sort of
connect this parabola

01:06:00.310 --> 01:06:03.740
with the saturated
value, which I know.

01:06:03.740 --> 01:06:07.300
And I know the transition
happens at the velocity when

01:06:07.300 --> 01:06:09.900
the atom moves further
than one wavelength in one

01:06:09.900 --> 01:06:12.020
spontaneous emission time.

01:06:12.020 --> 01:06:14.620
So therefore, based on
this very physical picture,

01:06:14.620 --> 01:06:18.970
and on the inside how low
velocities and high velocities

01:06:18.970 --> 01:06:23.820
connect together, I can actually
obtain the friction coefficient

01:06:23.820 --> 01:06:28.210
in this blue detuned standing
wave by taking the cooling rate

01:06:28.210 --> 01:06:33.680
and dividing it by the velocity
at which the atom moves

01:06:33.680 --> 01:06:36.590
one wavelength per
spontaneous emission time.

01:06:40.860 --> 01:06:44.190
And if I do that, I
obtain this result,

01:06:44.190 --> 01:06:46.650
which I have already
quoted earlier to you

01:06:46.650 --> 01:06:48.950
from the paper of
Cohen-Tonnoudji and Jean

01:06:48.950 --> 01:06:49.980
Dalibard.

01:06:49.980 --> 01:06:54.040
It looks fairly non-trivial with
power to the 6, power to the 5.

01:06:54.040 --> 01:06:57.362
But this is now the simple
perturbative results

01:06:57.362 --> 01:06:58.570
for the friction coefficient.

01:07:02.800 --> 01:07:05.360
Now we have the
friction coefficient.

01:07:05.360 --> 01:07:06.580
Let's take it further.

01:07:06.580 --> 01:07:09.420
I want to give you, in
this perturbative limit,

01:07:09.420 --> 01:07:12.510
I want to give you the
momentum diffusion coefficient.

01:07:12.510 --> 01:07:15.570
And then we will find in
the perturbative limit what

01:07:15.570 --> 01:07:18.480
is the lowest temperature
to which we can cool.

01:07:18.480 --> 01:07:20.050
So pretty much
I'll do everything

01:07:20.050 --> 01:07:23.550
as we've done before, but I use
the simple perturbative limit.

01:07:29.790 --> 01:07:34.450
So again, in order to calculate
the diffusion coefficient--

01:07:34.450 --> 01:07:36.740
the momentum diffusion
coefficient-- and the heating

01:07:36.740 --> 01:07:40.490
we need the fluctuations
of the force.

01:07:40.490 --> 01:07:43.600
And now, just remember, we
are in the perturbative limit.

01:07:43.600 --> 01:07:47.510
The atom is mainly
in the ground state,

01:07:47.510 --> 01:07:51.630
which is the upper
dressed level.

01:07:51.630 --> 01:07:54.620
It has only a little
excited stated mixture,

01:07:54.620 --> 01:07:56.760
so it will mainly
stay in this state.

01:07:56.760 --> 01:08:00.350
But then with this excited
stated mixture and this,

01:08:00.350 --> 01:08:03.610
power of the Rabi frequency,
it makes the transition

01:08:03.610 --> 01:08:05.210
to the other dressed state.

01:08:05.210 --> 01:08:09.030
But the other dressed state
is almost 100% excited state.

01:08:09.030 --> 01:08:11.040
So it will leave the
other dressed state

01:08:11.040 --> 01:08:12.990
almost immediately.

01:08:12.990 --> 01:08:16.540
So this could be a Quantum
Monte Carlo wave function result

01:08:16.540 --> 01:08:19.290
that the atom
experiences the force

01:08:19.290 --> 01:08:21.460
in the upper dressed level.

01:08:21.460 --> 01:08:24.689
Then it goes to the lower
dressed level, which is mainly

01:08:24.689 --> 01:08:28.060
the excited state, just
4 times 1 over gamma.

01:08:28.060 --> 01:08:30.939
And then it returns.

01:08:30.939 --> 01:08:35.340
So the picture now is that the
atom for almost all the time

01:08:35.340 --> 01:08:38.410
experiences the steady
state force, which

01:08:38.410 --> 01:08:40.130
is the blue dashed line.

01:08:40.130 --> 01:08:43.029
And there are only, when it
goes to the other dressed state,

01:08:43.029 --> 01:08:48.090
these small spikes where
the force has changed sign.

01:08:48.090 --> 01:08:52.250
And if you now calculate the
fluctuations of the force--

01:08:52.250 --> 01:08:58.750
the integral of f square--
once we calculate the square

01:08:58.750 --> 01:09:02.170
the small deviations
from the average force

01:09:02.170 --> 01:09:03.439
does not contribute.

01:09:03.439 --> 01:09:06.689
What contributes are the spikes.

01:09:06.689 --> 01:09:15.399
So all I do is now I take the
4 square in one of the spikes.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:26.220
And the force is nothing else
than the derivat-- remember

01:09:26.220 --> 01:09:28.580
we have a standing
wave a mu naught.

01:09:28.580 --> 01:09:31.390
The derivative of the
standing wave is the force.

01:09:31.390 --> 01:09:33.790
But if you have a
sinusoid lattice

01:09:33.790 --> 01:09:36.810
the force is K times the
amplitude of the lattice.

01:09:36.810 --> 01:09:41.779
I square it, so this
is the spike squared.

01:09:41.779 --> 01:09:43.960
Then I have to multiply
with the time 1

01:09:43.960 --> 01:09:49.740
over gamma, over which
the force stays the same.

01:09:49.740 --> 01:09:53.029
So this is, you can see, the
correlation time of the force.

01:09:53.029 --> 01:09:55.030
But then I have
to multiply, also,

01:09:55.030 --> 01:09:57.810
when I do an average over
many, sort of, you can see,

01:09:57.810 --> 01:10:02.440
trajectories, I have to
average over the probability

01:10:02.440 --> 01:10:08.760
that-- I have to multiply
with the probability

01:10:08.760 --> 01:10:10.490
that the atom is in
the dressed state

01:10:10.490 --> 01:10:13.390
1 and not in the
dressed state 2.

01:10:13.390 --> 01:10:15.190
It may take you a
few minutes just

01:10:15.190 --> 01:10:17.310
to think about
the combinatorics.

01:10:17.310 --> 01:10:20.790
But in the end all I do
is I take the 4 square,

01:10:20.790 --> 01:10:24.650
I multiply with correlation time
when the atom is in state 2,

01:10:24.650 --> 01:10:27.810
and get the probability
that the atom is in state 2.

01:10:27.810 --> 01:10:31.560
And when the atom is in
state 1, in my ensemble,

01:10:31.560 --> 01:10:33.970
it doesn't contribute at
all, because in state 1

01:10:33.970 --> 01:10:35.860
you're so close to
the average force

01:10:35.860 --> 01:10:39.280
that it doesn't contribute
with the fluctuation.

01:10:39.280 --> 01:10:41.780
Anyway, it's simple but subtle.

01:10:41.780 --> 01:10:44.860
But it's a one-liner.

01:10:44.860 --> 01:10:47.170
And now based on
this perturbative

01:10:47.170 --> 01:10:52.010
picture we have perturbatively
exact an expression

01:10:52.010 --> 01:10:55.040
for the heating rate.

01:10:55.040 --> 01:10:58.000
But now it's
interesting, the rate

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:04.580
gamma one, two, the rate to
switch between dressed energy

01:11:04.580 --> 01:11:11.230
levels always also appears in
the expression for the friction

01:11:11.230 --> 01:11:12.660
coefficient.

01:11:12.660 --> 01:11:17.620
So therefore, if
you're now asking

01:11:17.620 --> 01:11:22.430
what is the ultimate temperature
to which we can cool the atom?

01:11:22.430 --> 01:11:26.030
It is the ratio of this
analytic result for the heating

01:11:26.030 --> 01:11:28.340
coefficient divided
by the analytic result

01:11:28.340 --> 01:11:29.760
for the friction coefficient.

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:33.450
Pretty much everything
cancels out, and what remains

01:11:33.450 --> 01:11:35.940
is mu naught.

01:11:35.940 --> 01:11:38.300
And this is a remarkable result.

01:11:38.300 --> 01:11:41.880
It's highly non-trivial, and I
really enjoyed showing to you

01:11:41.880 --> 01:11:45.320
how simply it can be
derived by-- it's really

01:11:45.320 --> 01:11:46.810
just perturbation theory.

01:11:46.810 --> 01:11:50.730
But you have to put in the right
concepts from the dressed atom

01:11:50.730 --> 01:11:52.100
picture.

01:11:52.100 --> 01:11:54.940
So what we learn
is the following.

01:11:54.940 --> 01:11:57.780
If you have a
standing wave, and we

01:11:57.780 --> 01:12:01.770
cool with a stimulated
force, the lowest temperature

01:12:01.770 --> 01:12:05.652
is-- with a prefactor,
which I haven't calculated--

01:12:05.652 --> 01:12:08.330
the amplitude of
the standing wave.

01:12:08.330 --> 01:12:13.120
And that means that it is
impossible to ever localize

01:12:13.120 --> 01:12:15.820
atoms within a standing wave.

01:12:15.820 --> 01:12:19.900
Laser cooling cannot be used
to create atoms in an optical

01:12:19.900 --> 01:12:20.790
lattice.

01:12:20.790 --> 01:12:23.270
The temperature of
the atoms is always

01:12:23.270 --> 01:12:26.330
comparable to the
depths of the lattice.

01:12:26.330 --> 01:12:27.950
So therefore the
atoms will never

01:12:27.950 --> 01:12:30.691
be localized in one
well of the lattice.

01:12:33.460 --> 01:12:35.550
And this is generally valid.

01:12:35.550 --> 01:12:37.650
The assumption we
have made here is

01:12:37.650 --> 01:12:40.900
that we have a two level atom.

01:12:40.900 --> 01:12:43.360
A lot of you work with
atoms to optical lattices.

01:12:43.360 --> 01:12:46.040
And you often use evaporative
cooling, take a Bose Einstein

01:12:46.040 --> 01:12:49.110
condensate, which is pretty much
a [INAUDIBLE] temperature put

01:12:49.110 --> 01:12:50.490
it in optical lattice.

01:12:50.490 --> 01:12:55.160
But before '95, people studied
laser cooling and atoms

01:12:55.160 --> 01:12:56.700
in optical lattices.

01:12:56.700 --> 01:12:59.760
And this was only
possible because atoms

01:12:59.760 --> 01:13:02.220
can be cooled to
lower temperatures

01:13:02.220 --> 01:13:06.370
than we have derived here
because they are not two level

01:13:06.370 --> 01:13:07.660
atoms.

01:13:07.660 --> 01:13:10.760
So laser cooling
in a standing wave,

01:13:10.760 --> 01:13:14.350
localization of atoms in a
standing wave by laser cooling,

01:13:14.350 --> 01:13:18.811
is only possibly by physics
beyond what we have discussed.

01:13:18.811 --> 01:13:19.310
Colin?

01:13:19.310 --> 01:13:23.675
AUDIENCE: If you use something
like Raman's sideband cooling,

01:13:23.675 --> 01:13:26.342
you could-- like, yeah,
you'd kind of need

01:13:26.342 --> 01:13:29.980
three levels for that, but
you eliminated the third.

01:13:29.980 --> 01:13:32.890
Really, it's just that
it's two levels, right?

01:13:32.890 --> 01:13:36.430
PROFESSOR: If you do
Raman's sideband cooling,

01:13:36.430 --> 01:13:39.580
he posted-- I think,
in the next 10 minutes,

01:13:39.580 --> 01:13:41.440
I cover what you want to see.

01:13:41.440 --> 01:13:44.360
Because now it involves
two ground states.

01:13:44.360 --> 01:13:46.630
And I want to show you, if
you have two ground states,

01:13:46.630 --> 01:13:51.120
to Hyper fine-- Raman's
sideband cooling-- if you have

01:13:51.120 --> 01:13:54.180
two different ground
states there is no physics.

01:13:54.180 --> 01:13:57.230
And I briefly want
to touch upon that.

01:13:57.230 --> 01:13:59.790
We'll just kind of
fill in one thing here,

01:13:59.790 --> 01:14:02.430
and it is, well, if
you take everything

01:14:02.430 --> 01:14:05.590
I've told you seriously,
you would say OK, too bad.

01:14:05.590 --> 01:14:08.110
We cannot localize atoms
in an optical lattice

01:14:08.110 --> 01:14:10.390
because the temperature
is always comparable

01:14:10.390 --> 01:14:12.140
to the amplitude of the lattice.

01:14:12.140 --> 01:14:17.880
But by making the lattice
smaller and smaller and smaller

01:14:17.880 --> 01:14:21.050
I can reach lower and
lower temperatures.

01:14:21.050 --> 01:14:24.920
Well, yes, the some
extent that's possible.

01:14:24.920 --> 01:14:28.240
But what we have done here
is we've done approximations.

01:14:28.240 --> 01:14:31.160
We've only focused on
the stimulated force.

01:14:31.160 --> 01:14:33.440
We have not looked
at the recoil which

01:14:33.440 --> 01:14:35.620
comes in spontaneous emission.

01:14:35.620 --> 01:14:39.780
And therefore, the moment we
would make the optical lattice

01:14:39.780 --> 01:14:43.720
smaller than gamma then
we have to include heating

01:14:43.720 --> 01:14:45.560
by the spontaneous light force.

01:14:45.560 --> 01:14:50.800
And the result will be that
blue molasses cannot reach lower

01:14:50.800 --> 01:14:53.850
temperatures than
red detuned molasses.

01:14:53.850 --> 01:14:56.530
And for red detuned
molasses we have already

01:14:56.530 --> 01:15:00.040
discussed the famous Doppler
limit, which is gamma over 2.

01:15:09.840 --> 01:15:11.360
So that's what I
wanted to present

01:15:11.360 --> 01:15:13.560
to you with the
stimulated force.

01:15:13.560 --> 01:15:16.820
First, a more general
discussion using the real

01:15:16.820 --> 01:15:18.510
dressed atom picture.

01:15:18.510 --> 01:15:22.194
But now in the end, to fly
over using sort of the baby

01:15:22.194 --> 01:15:24.610
dressed atom picture, which
is simple perturbation theory.

01:15:31.050 --> 01:15:39.010
OK, so we've done the hard work.

01:15:39.010 --> 01:15:42.260
Now we want to have some
fun discussing the physics.

01:15:42.260 --> 01:15:45.970
And I'm realizing I've only
five, six, seven minutes left.

01:15:45.970 --> 01:15:48.630
I want to discuss three points.

01:15:48.630 --> 01:15:54.100
One is I want to give you all
the different pictures to find

01:15:54.100 --> 01:15:56.220
the potential of a dipole
trap, because we've

01:15:56.220 --> 01:15:58.110
encountered several.

01:15:58.110 --> 01:16:00.930
The second thing is I want
to have a discussion with you

01:16:00.930 --> 01:16:05.260
if the stimulated force is due
to electric or magnetic forces.

01:16:05.260 --> 01:16:08.420
And eventually, and we'll
be running out of time,

01:16:08.420 --> 01:16:11.120
I have to do that on
Wednesday to discuss

01:16:11.120 --> 01:16:13.440
the question of
energy conservation.

01:16:13.440 --> 01:16:16.630
If you cool the atoms
where does the energy go?

01:16:19.550 --> 01:16:25.620
So if you use the
stimulated force,

01:16:25.620 --> 01:16:27.970
it gives rise to
dipole potential.

01:16:27.970 --> 01:16:30.870
And using the Optical Bloch
Equations or the dressed atom

01:16:30.870 --> 01:16:34.340
picture, we found
this expression

01:16:34.340 --> 01:16:37.790
for the dipole potential.

01:16:37.790 --> 01:16:47.590
And there are at least four ways
how we could have derived it.

01:16:47.590 --> 01:16:51.050
One is the Optical Bloch
Equations, we did that.

01:16:51.050 --> 01:16:53.020
The dressed atom picture,
we did that today.

01:16:55.830 --> 01:16:59.100
Another picture is very
straightforward and simple.

01:16:59.100 --> 01:17:02.370
It just says that
the potential is

01:17:02.370 --> 01:17:05.560
the electric
potential of a dipole.

01:17:05.560 --> 01:17:11.570
And then all you have to know
is from the EC polarizability,

01:17:11.570 --> 01:17:15.740
if you drive an atom
with a laser field

01:17:15.740 --> 01:17:18.510
below resonance--
I mean that's just

01:17:18.510 --> 01:17:21.045
harmonic oscillator--
below resonance

01:17:21.045 --> 01:17:25.170
the harmonic oscillator is
in phase with the force.

01:17:25.170 --> 01:17:28.670
Above resonance, if you drive
a harmonic oscillator fast,

01:17:28.670 --> 01:17:32.350
the response of the harmonic
oscillator is in opposite,

01:17:32.350 --> 01:17:33.980
it's out of phase.

01:17:33.980 --> 01:17:37.310
So therefore, if your
potential is minus the E,

01:17:37.310 --> 01:17:41.310
you are in phase-- it is a
negative attractive potential.

01:17:41.310 --> 01:17:44.160
If the harmonic oscillator
is driven above resonance

01:17:44.160 --> 01:17:45.760
there is another
minus sign, you get

01:17:45.760 --> 01:17:49.500
plus the E, which becomes
a repulsive potential.

01:17:49.500 --> 01:17:51.574
So it's, look and
say, just the physics

01:17:51.574 --> 01:17:52.615
of a harmonic oscillator.

01:17:56.420 --> 01:17:58.810
There's one thing I like,
which is sometimes not

01:17:58.810 --> 01:18:01.210
taught in an atomic
physics course

01:18:01.210 --> 01:18:05.945
because it is the force on a
macroscopic dielectric object.

01:18:08.630 --> 01:18:12.640
So let's assume we
have an atom-- no, we

01:18:12.640 --> 01:18:13.660
don't have an atom.

01:18:13.660 --> 01:18:15.750
We have something
which is bigger.

01:18:15.750 --> 01:18:18.340
Let's assume a tiny
polystyrenes sphere.

01:18:18.340 --> 01:18:21.430
You can assume a
small sphere of glass.

01:18:21.430 --> 01:18:24.420
What happens if I
shine a laser beam

01:18:24.420 --> 01:18:27.200
on a small sphere of glass?

01:18:27.200 --> 01:18:33.420
Well, let me assume that
the laser beam is-- well,

01:18:33.420 --> 01:18:38.670
if the laser beam hits
this sphere right on,

01:18:38.670 --> 01:18:40.670
it's symmetric,
there is no force.

01:18:40.670 --> 01:18:43.540
So what we want to do is we
want to have a laser beam, shown

01:18:43.540 --> 01:18:46.560
here by this arrow,
which has a maximum here

01:18:46.560 --> 01:18:48.580
so the profile is like this.

01:18:48.580 --> 01:18:52.310
And we want to discuss
whether this sphere is sucked

01:18:52.310 --> 01:18:54.870
into the laser beam, this
would be an attractive force,

01:18:54.870 --> 01:18:57.170
or whether this
sphere is repelled.

01:18:57.170 --> 01:18:59.459
And all we want
to use is optics,

01:18:59.459 --> 01:19:00.500
the optics of refraction.

01:19:03.240 --> 01:19:06.450
When we have a laser beam
which is weak, medium, strong,

01:19:06.450 --> 01:19:09.460
strong here, and
for red detuning

01:19:09.460 --> 01:19:12.640
we have an index of refraction
which is larger than 1.

01:19:12.640 --> 01:19:15.470
So the sphere acts like a lens.

01:19:15.470 --> 01:19:17.980
So that leaves those
photons up and in,

01:19:17.980 --> 01:19:20.670
and those photons up and in.

01:19:20.670 --> 01:19:25.330
And when a photon is bent in,
the momentum of the photon

01:19:25.330 --> 01:19:26.300
has changed.

01:19:26.300 --> 01:19:29.150
And the momentum, of course,
the opposite momentum transfer,

01:19:29.150 --> 01:19:31.870
is imparted to the sphere.

01:19:31.870 --> 01:19:36.320
So in this case, we
have sort of-- we

01:19:36.320 --> 01:19:39.470
have more photons in this
part of the laser beam, which

01:19:39.470 --> 01:19:42.500
are bent up, than
photons are bent down.

01:19:42.500 --> 01:19:45.670
And this means the net
force is that the sphere is

01:19:45.670 --> 01:19:48.110
sucked into the laser beam.

01:19:48.110 --> 01:19:50.790
And if you go for
blue detuned light,

01:19:50.790 --> 01:19:53.250
where the index of
refraction is smaller than 1,

01:19:53.250 --> 01:19:55.690
it is the opposite.

01:19:55.690 --> 01:19:58.030
So the picture which
we have discussed here

01:19:58.030 --> 01:20:01.010
was for atoms form
microscopic objects.

01:20:01.010 --> 01:20:05.700
But you have, actually,
similar physics

01:20:05.700 --> 01:20:09.810
of a stimulated force for
mesoscopic and macroscopic

01:20:09.810 --> 01:20:10.740
objects.

01:20:10.740 --> 01:20:15.170
And then what matters whether
you trap or anti-trap,

01:20:15.170 --> 01:20:17.870
is whether the index of
refraction is larger than 1

01:20:17.870 --> 01:20:20.090
or smaller than one.

01:20:20.090 --> 01:20:23.350
And you know, two level
system for blue detuned light

01:20:23.350 --> 01:20:26.000
has an index of refraction
which is smaller than 1.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:28.880
And for red detuned
light our atomic clouds

01:20:28.880 --> 01:20:32.520
have an index of refraction
which is larger than 1.

01:20:32.520 --> 01:20:36.210
But this picture that you
can use the same set up,

01:20:36.210 --> 01:20:38.650
the same focus beam
and a similar dipole

01:20:38.650 --> 01:20:43.250
force to trap larger
objects is actually

01:20:43.250 --> 01:20:47.940
exploited in a different
field of physics,

01:20:47.940 --> 01:20:52.160
in biology, in the form
of optical tweezers.

01:20:52.160 --> 01:20:54.210
When actually in
the early '80s, when

01:20:54.210 --> 01:20:57.850
Steve Chu came to Bell Labs
and had discussions with Art

01:20:57.850 --> 01:21:03.380
Ashkin, they actually discussed
optical trapping, both of atoms

01:21:03.380 --> 01:21:09.590
and both of biological objects,
little microspheres, or cells.

01:21:09.590 --> 01:21:13.780
And it's sort of remarkable
that both approaches

01:21:13.780 --> 01:21:16.230
were realized within
the same year.

01:21:16.230 --> 01:21:18.440
So atoms were trapped in '86.

01:21:18.440 --> 01:21:21.740
And macroscopic objects
were manipulated,

01:21:21.740 --> 01:21:23.670
I think it's exactly
the same year.

01:21:23.670 --> 01:21:26.630
And as you know,
the optical tweezers

01:21:26.630 --> 01:21:32.030
is now an important technology
in biology and biophysics.

01:21:32.030 --> 01:21:34.970
For instance, you can
focus a laser beam

01:21:34.970 --> 01:21:37.660
and manipulate objects
within a living cell.

